            "id": "9cd0951fb0c44170a992f",
            "questionText": "In a physics lab, a monochromatic light with a wavelength of $!$\\lambda = 550 \\text{ nm}$!$ is shone through a single slit. Originally, the slit width is $!$b = 2.0 \\mu\\text{m}$!$, but it is then reduced to $!$b = 1.0 \\mu\\text{m}$!$. The diffraction pattern is observed on a screen placed $!$D = 1.5 \\text{ m}$!$ away from the slit. Determine the distance from the center of the central maximum to the first minimum on the screen for the reduced slit width of $!$b = 1.0 \\mu\\text{m}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "762763080b914a609339e",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the condition for the first diffraction minimum in a single-slit experiment. Choose the formula that correctly represents the relationship between the slit width, the diffraction angle, and the wavelength.",
